{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8fc7aa5-b8cf-4ef6-9a1e-3114b3ecce89","content":"\n\nHere's the `mcp.json` configuration for VS Code (place it at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` targeting your project.\n- Make sure your MCP server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport).\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or reload the window. Copilot agent mode will auto-discover the server and its tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"32232f8a-d411-4b5c-8b92-d8a7c7592d3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure an `mcp.json` file to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me check what's in their project to give accurate advice.","outputTokens":280},"id":"5deaee7f-082c-4068-967d-a42b461f329e","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:13.943Z","parentId":"c1ede710-3de0-4f5e-b52e-612cd00c1c8b"}
